article.description: Ann Wauters had 18 points and Becky Hammon added 16 to lead the New York Liberty past the defending champion Seattle Storm 79-67 Saturday night.
article.headline: Liberty pull into tie for third place in East
article.linkText: Wauters, Hammon lead Liberty past Storm
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Even with a 19-point lead, the New York Liberty
were expecting the defending champion Seattle Storm to make the
game close. When it happened, the Liberty didn't panic.

Ann Wauters had 18 points, Becky Hammon added 16 and New York
went 7-for-8 from the free throw line in the final 30 seconds to
hold off the Storm 79-67 Saturday night.

"They're a great team, they have a lot of great players,"
Hammon said. "You know they're going to make a push at you."

Elena Baranova had 14 points and nine rebounds, and Crystal
Robinson and Shameka Christon added 11 points apiece for New York
(13-12), which pulled into a tie with Washington for third place in
the Eastern Conference.

Lauren Jackson had 25 points and seven rebounds, and Sue Bird
added 12 points and 10 assists for Seattle (14-12), lost its second
straight since a six-game winning streak.

Leading by 12 at the break, the Liberty pushed their lead to
49-32 just two minutes into the second half. Reserve forward
Cathrine Kraayeveld hit a layup and a 3-pointer to give New York
its biggest lead of the game at 65-46 with 6:45 remaining.

"I don't think we played real well tonight," Jackson said.
"We needed to pick up the pace, but we just didn't."

The Storm then slowly chipped away. Bird made a 3 and a
fast-break layup to cut the deficit to 14 less than a minute later.
Jackson then scored seven straight points to make it 67-58 with
4:07 left.

After Baranova hit a 3 to push New York's lead back to 12,
Seattle scored seven straight points to pull within five at 70-65
with 45.7 seconds remaining but that was as close as it got.

"Every team is going to make a run," said Wauters, who shot
7-for-10 from the field. "They hit a couple of 3s, that helped
them come back in the game. We still really controlled the game
even at that point."

The Liberty, the top free-throw shooting team in the WNBA, then
sealed the win at the line. Hammon made a pair of free throws with
29.4 seconds left, Baranova went 1-for-2 about 9 seconds later, and
Robinson made all four of her attempts to push he lead back to 12
with 10 seconds remaining.

"When this team executes, they are fun to watch," New York
coach Pat Coyle said. "You have to dictate tempo against them.
When they take the ball out of the net it makes it a lot easier to
get back into our transition defense."

The Liberty had a season-high 23 assists -- including a game-high
nine by Vickie Johnson -- and finished 53 percent from the field.
Both teams shot well in the first half, as New York was 63 percent
(19-for-30) and Seattle 62 percent (16-for-26).

"We executed well, and shared the ball really well," Hammon
said. "They came out and tried to trap, and we did a good job of
making the extra pass."

The Storm were playing without second-leading scorer Betty
Lennox, who sprained her left wrist late in a loss at Indiana on
Thursday.

"We lose Betty's points, her energy," Storm coach Anne Donovan
said. "She takes a defender away from Lauren. So it changes the
flow of our offense for sure."

Iziane Castro Marques hit a pair of jumpers to give Seattle its
only lead of the game, 14-12 with 13:14 remaining in the first
half. The Liberty scored seven straight points, including a
3-pointer and fast-break layup by Robinson to take a 19-14 lead
with 11:49 left.

Castro Marques' jumper cut the Storm's deficit to 30-28 with
4:59 left.

New York then closed the period with a 14-4 run, including seven
points by Christon to take a 44-32 lead at halftime.
